it wasnt the message but a word president 
bush used that elevated eyebrows after his television speech on the 
deficit the other night 
there he was in about the most solemn setting at a presidents 
command a primetime oval office address only the fourth of 
bushs presidency and he used a phrase more appropriate to a 
bumper sticker 
and now let me tell you what this agreement will not do the 
president said it will not raise income tax rates personal or 
corporate it will not mess with social security in any way 
will not mess with 
brilliant choice of words said ken khachigian a san clemente 
calif lawyer who used to write oval office speeches for richard 
nixon and ronald reagan thats the conversational bush he 
said thats one of the reasons he is doing so well 
no mess was a bad choice said a student of language 
william lutz of rutgers university chairman of the committee on 
public doublespeak of the national council of teachers of english 
the language does not flow from the man it strikes our ear as 
artificial said lutz in a matter of such grave seriousness 
and in a formal address by a president people look for more formal 
language a more elevated tone would have been more appropriate 
if nothing else the issue shows the importance that can be 
attached to every presidential word especially those uttered in 
formal settings 
robin lakoff professor of linguistics at the university of 
california at berkeley thought bushs choice of mess was 
very characteristic of bush hes trying to be a regular guy 
american people like to see their presidents as populists 
said ms lakoff author of talking power the politics of 
language in our lives 
bush is by birth an aristocrat she said so he has to 
spend a whole lot of his energy proving that he isnt 
he used mess as though saying see i empathize with 
you she said i think it is too manipulative to work it 
doesnt work for me on the other hand he has an 80 percent 
popularity rating 
ms lakoff also commented on another phrase in the same speech 
bush said it is the best agreement that can be legislated now 
thats an insiders use of legislated usually legislators 
legislate 
ms lakoff said bush was expressing authority by choosing that 
buzzword 
mess says i talk your language im one of you she 
said legislated says i understand complicated issues i am at 
the hub of where things happen so you can trust me as an 
authority theyre two ways of appealing for trust 
fred mish the dictionary man comes down on bushs side 
its a little offbeat said mish editorial director of 
merriamwebster inc of springfield mass speaking of bushs use 
of legislated he added what he means seems clear enough 
as for mess thus spake mish its sort of an informal 
word in a fairly formal context its quite intentional and 
possibly effective 
if franklin roosevelt had said it it would have been almost 
unbelievable but the nature of public discourse has changed in the 
last 50 years 
