<DOCNO> AP901004-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are some key dates in the long 
negotiations to limit conventional arms in europe 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
october 1973 the united states and six nato allies open the 
mutual balanced force reduction mbfr talks in vienna with the 
soviet union and three of its warsaw pact allies 
april 1986 soviet president mikhail gorbachev announces a plan 
to break the stalemated talks 
june 1986 in the budapest appeal the warsaw pact proposes 
a broadening of the talks to include all alliance members 
dec 7 1988 gorbachev announces unilateral soviet troop 
reductions 
jan 10 1989 the two alliances convene the conventional 
forces in europe or cfe talks consisting of all 23 members of 
the two blocs 
feb 2 1989 the mbfr talks wind up after 470 meetings 
march 9 1989 the cfe talks open 
may 11 1989 gorbachev gives important proposals to secretary 
of state james a baker iii in moscow and the two sides make 
proposals and counterproposals at frequent intervals 
may 29 1989 president bush makes proposals at the nato 
summit 
dec 14 1989 both sides exchange draft treaty texts 
dec 23 1989 bush and gorbachev agree to try to complete a 
treaty by the end of 1990 
jan 31 1990 bush proposes troop limits of 195000 on each 
side in the central region plus 30000 in other areas for the 
united states 
june 27 1990 negotiators in vienna nail down the tricky 
issues of limits on tanks and armored troop carriers 
sept 27 1990 baker and soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze meeting in new york agree on the limits on the 
proportion of european arms any alliance member may hold in 
meetings over the previous week they agree to drop personnel 
ceilings from the treaty 
oct 3 1990 agreement in principal is announced by baker and 
shevardnadze after the final unresolved issue aircraft limits is 
put to rest 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

