<TEXT>
the united states and canada will open 
negotiations next year to dismantle barriers to free and open 
competition in the skies between the airlines of the two nations 
transportation secretary samuel k skinner said the talks could 
result in an unprecedented deregulation of air traffic across 
international borders and add up to 2 million passengers a year to 
what is already the worlds largest aviation market 
skinner and canadian transport minister doug lewis made the 
announcement in a joint statement issued simultaneously in 
washington and toronto on wednesday 
skinner told reporters that all aspects of air service between 
the two nations will be up for discussion when the talks begin in 
early 1991 
lewis said negotiators will explore the possibility of creating 
an open regime 
the goal airlines from each country would be allowed to operate 
between any point in one country and any point in the other as well 
as between points in the other country 
skinner said the possibility of permitting canadian airlines to 
open hubs in the united states and american air carriers to open 
hubs in canada also will be on the table 
in their statement skinner and lewis noted that the current 
aviation agreement between the two countries has remained basically 
unchanged since 1974 they said it is now out of step with the 
transportation needs of canada and the us 
we want an aviation market in which the flow of goods and 
services would be unimpedd by governmental economic regulation 
the two officials said 
skinner noted that the two countries have already deregulated 
their domestic airline industries and said that fact should make it 
easier to deregulate air service across their common border 
the united states and canada signed a freetrade agreement in 
1988 and skinner said that created a totally new economic 
atmosphere and the opportunity to expand and deregulate air links 
we will basically take down the barriers that exist he 
said 
about 13 million passengers fly between canada and the united 
states each year producing annual revenue of more than 2 billion 
us airlines carry about twothirds of the scheduled traffic 
about 11 million passengers a year while almost all of the charter 
passengers about 2 million a year are carried by canadian 
airlines 
skinner said growth of the uscanadian air market has been 
sluggish in recent years because of the restrictions the two 
countries impose to limit the numbers of air carriers and flights 
the national transportation policy announced by skinner earlier 
this year calls for improving access to international markets for 
us airlines the transportation secretary said the uscanada 
air negotiations will mark a good first step toward that objective 
tom lydon a lawyer for the air transport association the 
principal trade group of us airlines said member carriers 
generally support the new negotiations in part because the present 
air service treaty with canada is one of the more restrictive 
of all such international agreements 
for example only one airline from each country may operate on 
any route and us carriers would like to serve more cities in 
canada regardless of how many companies are doing so already he 
said 
</TEXT>
