<TEXT>
the childhood death rate in parts of the world 
where malnutrition is common can be cut in half by giving underfed 
children 2 worth of vitamin a annually according to a study 
released today 
doctors who conducted the study in india gave children the same 
amount of vitamin a that they would get in a healthy diet with 
dramatic results according to the study published in the new 
england journal of medicine 
the study was conducted by dr laxmi rahmathullah and colleagues 
from aravind childrens hospital in madurai india the united 
nations estimates that 20 million to 40 million children have at 
least mild vitamin a deficiency and nearly half of them live in 
india 
in an accompanying editorial dr gerald t keusch of new 
england medical center called the results positive impressive 
and convincing but said the 2 pricetag still might be too high 
for impoverished nations 
it is time that the international community did something more 
about this than talk he wrote 
the study was conducted on 15419 preschool children in southern 
india they were randomly selected to receive vitamins a and e or 
vitamin e alone 
during the oneyear study 125 children died but the risk of 
death among those taking vitamin a was only half that of those who 
got vitamin e alone 
the vitamin a appeared to reduce the risk of dying from diarrhea 
or other infections in malnourished children 
an earlier study conducted in indonesia reached similar 
conclusions 
