on april 14 authorities said 
connghan set two shotgun booby traps at the warehouse after a 
breakin in january during another burglary in march one booby 
trap was tripped but malfunctioned he dismantled one of the traps 
but told authorities he forgot to disarm the other 
connaghan said he set the traps because he was increasingly 
frustrated by breakins and the theft of expensive tools personal 
items and electronic equipment he needed for his work 
the case triggered overwhelming support for connaghan from 
residents who said they were fed up with the high crime rate some 
people put up signs warning their businesses also were booby 
trapped 
district attorney norm early said if officers did advise 
connaghan on how to dispose of a body it would not constitute a 
crime 
colorado has a make my day law that allows use of deadly 
force to protect householders from intruders but the district 
attorneys office said it only applied to people in fear of their 
lives 
prosecutors said connaghan was not at the warehouse at the time 
of the burglary and therefore not entitled to protection under the 
law 
connaghan was sentenced in august to pay 9500 in fines and 
restitution to mccombs family and was placed on six years 
probation 
