<TEXT>
scientists believe they are zeroing in on the gene 
responsible for marfan syndrome an inherited cause of heart 
disease but in a report released today they caution that no cure 
is in sight 
the researchers reported finding the general area of the gene 
an important step toward pinpointing the defective gene and finding 
out how it causes the disease according to the study in the new 
england journal of medicine 
people with marfan syndrome usually are tall and lanky they 
often suffer heart ailments that can cause death 
the dsease runs in families and finding its genetic roots 
should help doctors diagnose who is likely to have it even before 
birth but the disease also does its damage during fetal 
development so that simply replacing the defective gene with a 
good one later in life would not reverse the disease 
for the foreseeable future the discovery of the cause of 
marfan syndrome will be of primarily psychological benefit to 
patients dr reed e pyritz of johns hopkins hospital wrote in 
an editorial published with the study 
he said the biologic and technical problems of gene replacement 
make the task seem insurmountable at present 
the report was based on a genetic analysis of five families with 
the disease in finland it was conducted by dr leena peltonen and 
colleagues from the national public health institute in helsinki 
the researchers narrowed down the location of the defective gene 
to chromosome 15 one of the strings of genes that determines how 
people develop 
the findings have been widely known in medical circles for 
several months and efforts are under way to see if the same 
genetic pattern shows up in other families with the disease 
if they pinpoint the defective gene scientists will be able to 
figure out what it does normally and how it causes disease when it 
malfunctions 
some experts believe the crucial gene may turn out to be one 
that controls the bodys production of fibrillin a protein that 
helps make skin and blood vessels stretch 
</TEXT>
