iraq could survive for a matter of weeks at most 
against the multinational force in the persian gulf the 
international institute for strategic studies said thursday 
in cold war days nato commanders talked in terms of days and 
weeks of their capacity to sustain conventional battles 
institute director francois heisbourg said at a news conference to 
present an annual survey of global forces the military balance 
199091 
the situation is not very different given the nature of 
conflict in that part of the world he said adding that the 
impact of sanctions on iraq would also mean the conflict would 
not last terribly long 
analysts presenting the report said iraq totally rearmed 11 army 
divisions between the end of its eightyear war with iran in 1988 
and invading kuwait on aug 2 
but president saddam hussein was forced to abandon an attempt to 
raise 10 new divisions 100000 to 150000 troops for his nearly 
1millionstrong army because the nation of 16 million people 
simply does not have enough men the analysts said 
assessing iraqi strength and tactics if hostilities break out 
