a supreme court justice thursday refused to 
reinstate campaign contribution limits for californias 
gubernatorial and other state races to be decided next month 
justice sandra day oconnor rejected without comment an 
emergency plea to suspend a federal judges ruling that threw out 
contribution limits imposed by california voters in 1988 
the lower court ruling lets candidates for governor other 
statewide posts and some local offices exceed the contribution 
limits from now until election day nov 5 
us district judge lawrence karlton ruled on sept 25 the 
limits give an unfair advantage to incumbents karlton also tossed 
out a ban on transfers of funds between candidates that was imposed 
by the same ballot initiative 
his ruling invalidated proposition 73 which among other 
things limits individuals to a maximum of 1000 in contributions 
to a particular candidate per fiscal year the measure also limits 
political action committee donations to 2500 or 5000 per 
candidate per fiscal year depending on the size of the committee 
it is unclear what effect the ruling may have on the 
gubernatorial race between democrat dianne feinstein and republican 
pete wilson 
wilson who had only token opposition in the june primary 
raised 125 million through june and had 39 million in the bank 
