<TEXT>
the justice department on thursday stepped up 
its investigation of the steep rise in gasoline prices by 
subpoenaing records of major us oil companies 
the departments announcement that it had sought records from a 
large number of oil companies independent refiners and marketers 
signalled that the civil antitrust investigation was entering a new 
phase 
in august justice department lawyers began informally 
interviewing petroleum industry executives to seek explanations for 
the steep rise in gasoline prices since iraq invaded kuwait aug 2 
james f rill assistant attorney general for antitrust said 
the records being sought by civil investigative demands cids 
would enable investigators to examine more closely those 
explanations and also pursue some issues for which we dont yet 
have answers 
within two days of the invasion us oil companies raised their 
gasoline prices an average of 4 cents a gallon according to one 
survey another showed that wholesale gasoline prices jumped 95 
cents a gallon in the three days 
the public outcry over price rises of up to 15 cents a gallon 
prompted several major oil companies to freeze or roll back their 
wholesale costs 
we aggressively will pursue this investigation until we 
determine whether or not violations of antitrust law contributed to 
the rise in gasoline prices rill said in a statement 
to establish antitrust violations investigators would have to 
determine that producers refiners or marketers colluded to raise 
prices antitrust laws carry both civil and criminal penalties 
the department has not opened a criminal investigation into the 
price hikes to do so prosecutors would have to convene a grand 
jury 
the federal trade commission the energy department and several 
state attorneys general are assisting the justice departments 
investigation 
rill said the interviews with petroleum industry executives 
developed substantial information about the nature of crude oil 
and gasoline markets and how they behaved in the wake of the august 
2 invasion 
it also provided us with an opportunity to have the parties 
explain the factors that caused them to raise gasoline prices he 
said 
the departments antitrust division will continue to interview 
executives of oil companies as well as independent refiners and 
marketers and collect price and supply information rill said 
the average pump price of gasoline has risen 271 cents a gallon 
since the invasion according to a survey issued this week by the 
american automobile association crude oil prices have nearly 
doubled and the threat of war in the persian gulf have produced 
wild price gyrations on commodities markets 
oil company spokesmen expressed confidence that investigators 
would conclude there was no illegal conduct 
mobil oil corp spokesman john lord predicted that the justice 
department probe would result in the same conclusion that antitrust 
investigators reached when they found no evidence of price gouging 
during a jump in heating oil prices last winter 
when the cold weather passed the prices fell but the 
investigations continued and when the investigations were 
completed as usual they found no price gouging whatsoever lord 
said that will be the case again 
mike libbey a spokesman for chevron corp said that gasoline 
prices went up in august to keep pace with the rising cost of crude 
oil which shot up after the invasion 
we are quite confident there was absolutely no price gouging 
of any kind libbey said 
