<DOCNO> AP901004-0104 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
beginning friday seats by exit doors on us 
airlines will be restricted by government order to the ablebodied 
only 
the federal aviation administration regulation says only people 
able and willing to open exit doors in an emergency and help flight 
crews evacuate the airplane will be seated in rows adjacent to 
them 
those barred from seats near exit doors include parents with 
small children people too frail to operate the door passengers 
with broken limbs or other disabilities that would inhibit 
movement obese people children under 15 and the blind 
the faa regulation limits seating in exit rows to passengers who 
can locate the door quickly follow instructions for its use are 
physically able to open the heavy doors and can judge whether it is 
safe to leave the aircraft 
they must also understand verbal and handsignaled instructions 
from flight attendants and be able to get around obstacles to lead 
other passengers off the aircraft 
at the time the regulation was issued last january organizations 
representing the blind called it discriminatory and said it would 
reduce a blind persons chances to survive an airplane crash 
some airlines already bar blind travelers from exitdoor seats 
and several blind people have been arrested in recent years for 
refusing to move from the seats 
a lobbying effort to prevent implementation of the regulation 
proved unsuccessful 
under the new procedures gate agents at each airport will 
assign the exit row seats to passengers who meet the new 
requirements and appear able and willing to perform emergency 
functions 
information cards will be provided at exit row seats describing 
the functions passengers sitting there may have to perform during 
an emergency 
flight attendants will describe these functions before each 
flight 
this is an important safety initiative said william hoover 
executive vice president of the air transport association which 
represents the nations airlines 
airline accidents are rare but when they do happen it is 
essential that the people seated in exit rows are capable of 
hearing and understanding instructions opening emergency exits and 
assisting their fellow passengers in an evacuation of the 
aircraft hoover said 
the faa describes an exit row seat as one from which passengers 
may go directly to an exit without stepping first into an aisle 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

