<TEXT>
new england telephone and new york telephone 
have agreed to pay 14 million to the us treasury and cut 
longdistance rates 355 million to resolve allegations they 
overcharged customers through a subsidiary the federal 
communications commission said thursday 
the payment is a voluntary contribution and doesnt constitute a 
fine the fcc said 
under the consent decree nynex corp admitted no guilt and the 
fcc said it made no findings of wrongdoing and was ending its 
enforcement action nynex is the regional parent company of new 
england telephone and new york telephone 
the fcc said in february that it intended to fine the two 
telephone companies 14 million over apparent violations of fcc 
rules governing transactions between regulated telephone companies 
and unregulated affiliates 
the fcc had ordered the companies to return 355 million to 
customers because of alleged 1185 million in overcharges to the 
companies by materiel enterprises co an unregulated nynex 
purchasing subsidiary 
nynex agreed to the 355 million rebate to be made within 30 
days and said the two phone companies would reduce their capital 
accounts by 326 million to remove the alleged excess profits on 
plant and equipment bought from the purchasing subsidiary 
local phone rates wont be affected 
we hope this puts to rest any questions concerning nynexs 
desire to comply with all fcc regulations and policies in 
transactions among affiliate companies nynex chairman william c 
ferguson said in a statement 
the agreement ends one of several pending federal or state 
actions against nynex one of the seven regional bell holding 
companies created in 1984 from the old bell system 
nynex also has been the focus of investigations that new york 
telephone suppliers helped pay for bawdy parties and prostitutes at 
annual conventions of company employees in florida from 1984 to 
1988 nynex has denied that any ratepayer funds were involved in 
the conventions 
in may the justice department filed a onecount criminal 
indictment alleging that nynex had violated the information 
services restrictions in the 1982 consent decree that created the 
regional bell companies nynex denied any wrongdoing 
on wednesday new york state utility regulators authorized a 
study into whether nynex should be forced to divest new york 
telephone 
toby webb nynex vice president for government affairs said 
thursday he could not estimate how much the 355 million rebate 
would affect longdistance prices for new york and new england 
phone customers 
webb said nynex had agreed to the latest consent decree to avoid 
a potentially long court battle over accounting and purchasing 
procedures that no longer were in effect materiel enterprises was 
merged into new york telephone and new england telephone earlier 
this year making materiel a fully regulated company under fcc 
rules 
the agreement is preferable to engaging in prolonged 
litigation over past events and practices which have been 
changed webb said 
the 14 million contribution to the treasury will be paid by 
nynex shareholders webb said and will not affect rates 
