<TEXT>
a vaccine that prevents bacterial meningitis 
and other lifethreatening diseases now can be given to infants as 
young as two months to protect them when they most need it 
the food and drug administration in approving thursday use of 
the vaccine at younger ages said new studies show it is safe and 
effective for these infants and could prevent hundreds of deaths a 
year 
the vaccine was approved in 1988 for use in children 18 months 
and older and later for use in children 15 months and older 
however bacterial meningitis and other diseases caused by the 
haemophilus influenzae type b bacteria take their heaviest toll in 
infants ages six to 12 months 
the vaccine has significantly reduced incidence of the 
haemophilus b diseases in children 18 months and older but 
physicians still diagnose about 10000 cases of haemophilus 
meningitis a year mostly in children under 18 months the fda 
said 
about 500 of these children die and of those who survive about 
3800 children suffer blindness deafness mental retardation and 
other neurological complications the fda said 
when the vaccine was first approved federal health officials 
said data were not available to show the vaccine was effective in 
younger children 
but a recently completed twoandahalf year multiracial and 
multiethnic study of more than 60000 infants less than six months 
old showed the vaccine was safe and would protect against the 
haemophilus b diseases the fda said 
the vaccine can be given at the same intervals as the 
diphtheria tetanus and pertussis vaccine two months four months 
and six months the agency said a booster dose would be given when 
the child is 15 months or older 
researchers found only mild and transient side effects among the 
infants in the study including swelling and warmth at the 
vaccination site and occasional fever 
besides bacterial meningitis the vaccine is effective against 
epiglottitis which is an often fatal inflammation of the flap that 
covers the breathing tubes pneumonia septicemia and septic 
arthritis 
the vaccine is not effective against viral meningitis 
the vaccine marketed under the name hibtiter is made by praxis 
biologics inc and is distributed by lederle laboratories both 
part of american cyanamid of wayne nj 
</TEXT>
