charged the two with conspiracy interstate transportation of 
obscene material aiding and abetting and engaging in a business of 
selling obscene matter 
if convicted niekerk and gallagher could be sentenced up to 25 
years in prison and fined as much as 125 million the company 
faces a maximum fine of 25 million 
the indictment resulted from a series of 24 searches in the los 
angeles area conducted earlier this year by the the fbi and los 
angeles police the justice department said 
the videocassettes showed a variety of sexual acts including 
group sex and lesbianism the department said 
denver defense attorney arthur schwartz who represents niekerk 
said evidence will show that the company had never shipped its 
videocassettes to oklahoma until it was lured into doing so by 
undercover federal agents 
they were really ensnared into doing it schwartz said 
the lawyer charged that justice department chose to bring 
charges against his client in oklahoma to take advantage of 
conservative moral standards in that part of the country 
the approach of the government in trying to regulate access to 
sexually oriented material is to go to the most conservative areas 
in the united states in an effort to pressure companies located in 
more liberal areas out of existence schwartz said 
are the people in tulsa going to decide what the people in new 
york feel they have a right to have 
federal juries are allowed to apply prevailing community 
standards in deciding whether material is obscene what may be 
found to be obscene in utah or oklahoma may not be considered so by 
a jury in another federal jurisdiction 
