the united states is responding to the 
unification of germany by altering its strategy in europe to a 
military presence rather than troops massed near the borders a top 
pentagon official said wednesday 
forward deployed forces will be smaller with greater emphasis 
on mobility and versatility than in the current nato structure to 
allow maximum flexibility in times of crisis said army maj gen 
john seawall 
the vice director for strategic plans and policy and two other 
defense department officials described for the senate armed 
services committee details of the unification and its impact on 
american and nato troops 
as the soviet union withdraws its forces from what was east 
germany with a target for completion of 1994 the military 
situation undergoes significant changes 
in the past the united states and its nato allies maintained 
forces shouldertoshoulder with the best defense closest to the 
warsaw pact nations under the new strategy the concept is 
defense of the borders as opposed to defense on the border 
seawall said 
stephen hadley assistant secretary of defense for internationl 
security policy said that based on dramatic changes in europe the 
withdrawal of soviet troops and the expected treaty to reduce 
conventional forces a new nato force is warranted 
the allies will move toward a reduced reliance on nuclear 
forces smaller and restructured active forces which are highly 
versatile and rely increasingly on multinational corps composed of 
national units and greater reliance on reserves and the ability to 
reconstitute larger forces as and when necessary 
