tropical storm klaus bore down 
thursday on the eastern caribbean after causing severe flooding on 
the french island of martinique where six people were reported 
dead and two missing 
the national hurricane center in miami said klaus the 11th 
named storm of the atlantic hurricane season had sustained winds 
of 60 mph and could grow into a hurricane by friday 
hurricane warnings were issued for the leeward islands along an 
arc from the french and dutch island of st martinst maarten in 
the north to the british colony of montserrat in the south 
tropical storm warnings remained in effect for martinique and its 
sister island of guadeloupe 
the storm has been showing signs of getting stronger and 
were forecasting the possibility of it becoming a hurricane within 
the next 24 hours said forecaster miles lawrence at the 
hurricane center 
klaus was expected to pass near the sparsely populated island of 
barbuda late thursday or early friday the center reported 
tropical storms are upgraded to hurricanes when their maximum 
sustained winds reach 74 mph 
the hurricane center said rainfall of 10 to 15 inches was 
possible for the islands of the northeastern caribbean that could 
trigger flash flooding and mudslides 
stan cieniewicz administrative officer for the pancaribbean 
disaster preparedness and prevention project in antigua said 
commercial airlines were flying to the region as scheduled 
he said authorities in guadeloupe warned residents to move 
cattle to protected areas to avoid long road trips and to keep 
away from rivers that could overflow in heavy rains 
at 6 pm edt klaus was centered near latitude 170 north and 
longitude 610 west or about 55 miles east of antigua it was 
moving northwest at 6 mph with tropical stormforce winds 
extending 115 miles from its center 
earlier klaus dumped torrential rain on martinique a french 
overseas department of 336000 inhabitants where six people were 
reported drowned in floodwaters that reached nearly 10 feet in 
places hundreds of people were evacuated from their homes as rain 
continued for a second day thursday 
among the dead were two sisters aged 8 and 14 who were swept 
from a bridge wednesday in st joseph authorities said rescuers 
found their bodies thursday 
four men were drowned in different parts of the island they 
included a 56yearold farmer who fell from his tractor into a 
flooded ditch 
two fishermen a father and son were reported missing 
thursday in riviere pilote officials told radio caribbean 
international that the local outdoor market and soccer stadium were 
under 5 feet of water 
jocelyne van elverdinghe an aide to prefect jeanclaude roure 
the french governments representative on the island said flooding 
forced 750 people from their homes in lamentin 
schools were closed throughout the island flooding disrupted 
telephone and electrical service 
in barbados southeast of martinique floodwaters forced the 
evacuation of a few families overnight and temporarily blocked some 
roads although the major tourist hotels on the western coast were 
unaffected 
lightning knocked out electricity across the island wednesday 
night 
high wind downed utility poles and trees in dominica to the 
north 
