<TEXT>
the last time josef felder attended a parliament 
session at the reichstag the future looked ominous as he and other 
opposition lawmakers battled vainly against growing nazi powers 
on thursday however felder returned to the building full of 
hope for the newly united germany 
i believe we have a good development in the sense of securing 
democracy said felder 90 the only member of the prewar 
parliament to attend the opening session 
felder took a seat next to president richard von weizsaecker to 
observe the first meeting of parliament in the reichstag since dec 
9 1932 when felder was a newly elected deputy in a nation in 
chaos as nazis consolidated power 
in the coming years felder would face nazi harassment flee 
underground and ultimately be sent to a concentration camp 
adolf hitler dissolved the legislature after he was named 
chancellor on jan 30 1933 and called new elections a fire 
gutted the reichstag before the vote was held march 5 
felder a social democrat from bavaria was reelected but 
faced increasing threats from the nazis the regime had already 
jailed many opposition communists and socialists the first targets 
of hitlers repression 
more than 100 members of the reichstag were killed or 
imprisoned 
the election campaign in february 1933 was exceptionally 
difficult for the opposition the social democrats were forbidden 
access to the press by hitler recalled felder 
after the nazis marched into bavaria on march 9 1933 felder 
and other lawmakers changed apartments to avoid arrest determined 
to take their seats in parliament 
felder recalled the tumultuous march 23 1933 session held in 
the nearby kroll opera when hitler forced through a plan allowing 
his government to make laws without the reichstags approval some 
of the social democrats were called scoundrels by crowds 
felder attended a parliament meeting may 17 1933 when a 
resolution calling for equal treatment of germany at the geneva 
disarmament convention was debated it was his last session 
in july the nazis banned the social democrats and felder fled 
to austria 
he continued underground work under an assumed name until 1934 
when the nazi threat forced him to flee for czechoslovakia 
but fearing reprisals against his family felder returned to 
bavaria and was thrown into the dachau concentration camp outside 
munich for two years 
he worked as an accountant following the war and gradually 
returned to politics in 1957 he was elected to the west german 
legislature in bonn the bundestag the west german parliament is 
also the name of the new german legislature 
after his third term expired in 1969 felder devoted himself to 
political education traveling thousands of miles each year to talk 
to school children about his experiences 
parliament president rita suessmuth on thursday warmly welcomed 
felder who said it was a great satisifcation to attend the 
historic meeting 
felder warned the new government must not permit the rise of 
obsessive nationalism which would endanger everything we 
achieved through negotiations with our allies 
