<TEXT>
a technical foulup by state officials 
shouldnt block oregons initiative petition process the oregon 
supreme court said thursday in explaining its decision to return 
five measures to the nov 6 ballot 
the court had no desire to entirely thwart the right of 
citizens to propose laws and amendments to the constitution and 
enact or reject them independently of the legislature chief 
justice edwin peterson wrote in the opinion written sept 28 and 
released thursday 
the unanimous ruling overturned a lower court decision that 
removed five of 11 measures from the ballot 
the problems began when a state committee missed a deadline for 
certifying statements for the ballot that explained what the 
measures would cost marion county judges invalidated those 
statements because of the missed deadline 
marion county circuit judge richard barber later invalidated 
five measures because they wouldnt be accompanied by the cost 
estimates 
the measures targeted by barbers ruling would limit property 
taxes shut down the trojan nuclear plant ban some nonrecyclable 
packaging allow tax credits for private schooling and set up a 
pilot work program for welfare applicants 
the ninemember supreme court reversed barber but upheld the 
lower court decisions to keep the estimates off the ballot 
despite the failure to meet the deadlines on fiscal impact 
