he arrived in time for the tidal wave of great 
society activism championed social concerns during the 
pennypinching reagan era and leaves as he came fighting for civil 
rights 
rep augustus hawkins 83 chairman of the house education and 
labor committee is a black man who never played racial politics a 
liberal who inspires affection among conservatives a courtly 
gentleman who rarely gives up or gives in 
the diminutive softspoken democrat is retiring this year after 
28 years in congress representing watts the los angeles 
neighborhood notorious for the riots that tore it apart in the 
1960s 
in the brave new capitol hill world of sound bites cynicism and 
big money the void left by hawkins departpre may not be 
immediately obvious but there will be one ask any education 
labor or civil rights lobbyist the senior republican on his 
committee even rep tom downey who bested him in a recent dispute 
over how to channel childcare money to states and parents 
this institution is going to miss him terribly said downey 
dny 
he has been a relentless pursuer of social justice said 
michael edwards chief lobbyist for the national education 
association he has very deeply held principles and a great sense 
of mission and yet he was always able to bring people together 
hawkins basic philosophy that government must help its less 
fortunate citizens hasnt changed much since he was elected to 
the california assembly in 1934 
i truly believe every person in our country is entitled to 
equal opportunities if we give them those opportunities it will 
help everybody else thats good ordinary common sense he said 
in an interview last week 
the son of a britishborn adventurer who moved his family to the 
united states after exploring africa hawkins won his house seat in 
1962 he was the first black member from a western state and one 
of the first things he did was sponsor the equal employment section 
of the landmark 1964 civil rights act 
it was an early triumph in a congressional career that has 
spanned eras of plenty and parsimony pendulum swings in political 
thought and the inevitable mixture of achievements and 
disappointments 
chief among the latter was the 1978 humphreyhawkins full 
employment bill which put forth an admirable goal but lost a 
federal job guarantee before passage its been an outright 
failure in terms of implementation hawkins said bluntly no 
ones taken it seriously beginning with the carter 
administration 
the widely supported 1988 welfare reform law with its 
requirement that some recipients take jobs was another setback 
from hawkins perspective workfare is a punitive approach to 
forcing people off the rolls he declared on the floor 
it was an unusually harsh stand for a man who despite his 
enduring new deal concerns generally prefers compromise to 
confrontation 
hawkins grasp of political reality was put to the test in 1984 
when he became committee chairman amid rampant conservatism and a 
scarcity of domestic resources for the most part he adapted well 
building coalitions and inching ahead where possible 
if you only have a potato the only thing you can make is 
potato soup you cant make stew said bob mcglotten chief 
lobbyist for the aflcio under severe circumstances gus has 
done a tremendous job to make sure the educational systems in our 
society dont fall apart 
the kind of money hawkins wanted to spend on education and 
programs for disadvantaged children wasnt available but he 
settled for modest gains and was rewarded with nearunanimous 
passage of many major education bills 
there was far more contention in the labor area including 
protracted battles over raising the minimum wage and guaranteeing 
unpaid family leaves to workers but civility was always the order 
of the day 
we dont have any animosity we have differences said fred 
krebs manager of the us chamber of commerces labor and human 
resources department 
the same civility characterized hawkins relations with 
republicans on the committee who recently threw him a retirement 
party among his gifts was a homemade gavel to crack crabs and a 
gag picture of downey with a forged inscription that said i 
really enjoyed working closely with you 
im very saddened that he is leaving said rep bill 
goodling rpa the senior republican on hawkins committee he 
is one of the finest gentlemen ive ever met 
the two men had a close partnership with the chairman often 
testing his ideas on goodling and molding them to attract broader 
support 
if he doesnt agree with what im trying to do i try to find 
out why i know i will get the same disagreements from others 
hawkins said if i can make modifications well get something 
done if you are really interested in results why not be 
cooperative 
hawkins so lightskinned he is often thought to be white has 
never chaired the congressional black caucus and prefers to cast 
issues in economic rather than racial terms 
he has promoted education health care and nutrition for the 
needy and been instrumental in securing passage of many civil 
rights laws that opened up opportunities for minorities and others 
ironically as he leaves congress hawkins is once again trying 
to restore some of the protections he first fought for in 1964 
bush is threatening to veto this years kennedyhawkins civil 
rights bill although hawkins said he amended it 22 times to try to 
please the administration 
in some ways were back where we were hawkins said it is 
discouraging but not to the point where were giving up you have 
this ebb and flow in american politics you win a few and you 
lose a few by and large you try to be incremental in making 
advances 
when hawkins retires he wont vanish onto the chesapeake bay in 
his beloved fishing boat instead he intends to speak volunteer 
and organize on behalf of job corps head start and other programs 
he fostered in congress you dont have to be in elective office 
to make a difference hawkins said theres lots of things to 
do and in between ill do a little fishing 
