<TEXT>
harold pinter the most influential playwright of 
his generation approaches his 60th birthday as an angry artist who 
hasnt written a fulllength play in 12 years 
to celebrate his birthday on oct 10 pinter is being remembered 
with a flurry of revivals and the delayed publication of a 
decadesold novel but there also is a sense among admirers that he 
has momentarily lost or squandered his gifts 
the man who turned the conversational pause into an emotional 
minefield is now known as much for his volatility as for his 
creative talent 
angry old man read the headline of a sept 16 cover story 
in britains sunday correspondent magazine focusing on his personal 
belligerence not his literary output 
in the late 1950s and throughout the next decades pinter 
codified a style steeped in verbal evasion and violence menace 
both spoken and not its effect was felt in the united states in 
the plays of sam shepard and david mamet and throughout british 
literature which suddenly had a new adjective pinteresque 
such plays as the birthday party and the homecoming 
examined the sour even horrifying underside of domestic rituals 
their workingclass milieu reflects pinters early life as the son 
of a jewish tailor from londons east end he began his career in 
the provinces as an actor 
in old times and betrayal he took a literary scalpel to 
highly charged erotic triangles 
betrayal written in 1978 was his last fulllength play 
reflecting on his career right now colleagues wonder whether hes 
capable of another one 
maybe hes said all he wanted to say says actress eileen 
atkins who starred in pinters brief play mountain language 
two years ago 
he hasnt got a play to write alas sir peter hall his 
longtime director says 
but he has many works worth reviving 
this month hall began rehearsals for a 25thanniversary 
production of the homecoming which he previously directed in 
london and on broadway and filmed in 1973 the play originally 
starred pinters first wife actress vivien merchant who died in 
1982 two years after their divorce 
his first major play 1958s the birthday party is on 
national tour and arrives in london on nov 20 
betrayal comes around again next year opening jan 22 
1991 at north londons almeida theater rehearsals start in april 
for a west end revival of the caretaker which pinter himself 
will direct 
all of which reminds admirers how a onceprolific output has 
dried up in the 1980s pinters only stage plays have been 
oneacts a kind of alaska 1982 one for the road 1984 
and the 20minute mountain language 1988 
even his new novel the dwarfs published oct 1 
resuscitates a work first begun and then abandoned more than 30 
years ago 
ive been very busy doing a lot of other things pinter said 
in a radio interview last month for the british broadcasting corp 
i havent any plans to write a play at the moment 
these days its pinters politics not his plays that make 
headlines 
yanquis go home the writer argued in britains independent 
on sunday newspaper in may the piece was a broadside against 
american policy in latin america 
two years earlier pinter and his second wife lady antonia 
fraser formed the 20th july group a forum for antitory opinion 
designed to oppose the policies of conservative prime minister 
margaret thatcher 
i strongly feel its my job as a citizen of this country to 
keep an eye on these things he sad in the bbc interview 
when not distinguishing himself with his political 
outspokenness pinter raises eyebrows with his choice of projects 
a former actor he has turned more and more to directing shows 
that scarcely seem worth his time in 1986 he directed faye 
dunaway in circe and bravo by american writer donald freed to 
mixed reviews 
in may he staged an american satire jane stanton hitchcocks 
vanilla on the west end the play received harsh reviews and 
closed seven weeks later 
screenwriting also keeps him occupied having written such 1960s 
classics as the servant accident and the gobetween 
he began the last decade adapting john fowles the french 
lieutenants woman 
he wrote two recent movies the handmaids tale released 
last spring and the imminent the comfort of strangers based 
on the ian mcewan novel 
pinter told the bbc that it was absolute nonsense however 
to assume his playwriting days were finished 
theres nothing id love more he said im 60 any minute 
and ive got plenty left in me i think 
