public enemy no 1 a communist plot 
nervepoison 
in the 1950s opponents of fluoridation marshaled rhetoric and 
research to fight what they called the poisoning of public water 
supplies some doctors linked fluoride to indigestion deafness 
and skin and mental diseases 
today fluoride is mainstream toothpaste tubes blare it 
bottled drinks and mouth rinses contain it and doctors recommend 
it sixtyone percent of americans live in communities with 
fluoridated public water 
but the debate is far from over 
take jody morgenegg who gathered signatures and handed out 
fliers seeking to stop the scotia village board from putting 
fluoride in the water system 
its carcinogenic she said we feel its not appropriate 
to adulterate the water with it 
or jim palmer one of several board trustees who voted to 
fluoridate village water earlier this year its going to protect 
the children in the years their teeth are really forming 
the board won and scotia has been fluoridating its water since 
march 
most major american health organizations including the us 
public health service the american dental association and the 
american medical association have endorsed fluoridation and cite 
hundreds of studies that show fluoride reduces dental caries most 
health organizations recommend one part per million when 
fluoridating drinking water 
its a safe and effective means of preventing tooth decay 
said darrell sanders fluoridation engineer with the federal 
centers for disease control 
but a vocal minority condemns fluoride as an industrial waste 
product that not only mottles teeth but kills thousands of people 
every year 
if youre drinking fluoridated water for 20 30 years youre 
probably increasing your cancer risks by 5 to 15 percent john 
yiamouyiannis a biochemist in delaware ohio said 
this year debate over fluoride rose a notch with the release of 
a study by the national toxicology program showing that some male 
rats given high doses of fluoride in water suffered higher rates of 
bone cancer than rats and mice on lower doses 
the author of the study dr john bucher said the results 
provided only equivocal evidence that fluoride is linked to 
cancer 
scientists first linked the mottling of teeth to fluoride early 
this century in parts of the southwest they found the condition 
often called colorado brown stain or texas teeth and known 
today as fluorosis in places with high natural levels of fluoride 
in drinking water fluoride a compound of the element fluorine is 
found in rocks and soil and in at least trace amounts in natural 
water supplies 
later research among children including pilot studies in 
newburgh ny and grand rapids mich in the 1940s showed that 
controlled amounts of fluoride in water sharply reduced tooth 
decay 
at first scientists were unclear why today fluoride is 
believed to reduce the solubility of enamel in acid and can 
remineralize enamel that has suffered decay 
since then fluoridation has spread 
the pennsylvania legislature is considering a bill that would 
require most water companies in the state to fluoridate at least 
eight other states have passed similar bills said dr h william 
gross chairman of partners for better oral health a coalition of 
groups backing the pennsylvania bill 
the reduction in dental caries in the decades since fluoride was 
introduced is substantial the rate of tooth decay has declined by 
as much as 75 percent to 80 percent since the 1940s according to a 
1988 study by the national institute for dental research 
but opponents of fluoridation attribute the decline to better 
infant nutrition and dental hygiene and contend most of the 
studies linking fluoride to tooth decay reduction are biased 
instead they say fluoride is a lethal byproduct of the 
phosphate industry 
dr albert burgstahler a professor at the university of kansas 
said he has treated people for fluoridation poisoning chronic 
fatigue headaches and gastrointestinal problems 
when patients switch to nonfluoridated water they found that 
their symptoms cleared up burgstahler said 
its the nonspecific syndrome said stephen corbin a 
dental public health specialist with the cdc none of that stuff 
has been attributed to fluoridation exposure 
