<TEXT>
is britain europes economic miracle of the 
1980s in a recession 
it depends whom you ask 
prime minister margaret thatcher says no she criticizes 
voices of gloom for exaggerating shortterm economic 
difficulties and insists interest rates will stay high until the 
106 percent inflation rate is tamed 
but many business people and economists say yes britains 
largest employers group the confederation of british industry is 
calling for a cut in 15 percent interest rates to to ensure that 
the recession is not any deeper than it needs to be 
britains economy is in a recession and there is now room for 
a gradual easing in interest rates said david kern chief 
economist of national westminster bank 
britons have enjoyed eight years of sustained economic growth 
which was thought to have ended a cycle of high inflation and high 
interest rates now the country is suffering what many economists 
call the same old symptoms and is putting in the worst performance 
of the major industrialized countries 
the generally accepted definition of a recession is two 
consecutive quarters of negative or zero economic growth one of 
the difficulties however is pinpointing when a recession has 
begun 
mrs thatcher addressing the welsh confederation of british 
industry last week complained that newspapers already have 
proclaimed the beginning of a world recession a return to 
stagflation and an end to the united kingdom economic miracle 
she said every new statistic including the latest monthly 
survey by the confederation of british industry is interpreted as 
heralding the onset of a major economic downturn 
the confederation survey showed confidence in britains 
manufacturing had hit the lowest point in eight years and provided 
clear evidence the economy had moved into recession 
business risks talking itself into a completely unjustified 
mood of doom and gloom a kind of artificial psychological 
trough deputy prime minister sir geoffrey howe said last week 
chancellor of the exchequer john major said the word recession 
implies a slump as deep as the great depression 
we are not in those sorts of circumstances he said we 
have a significant but necessary slowdown at the moment 
but karl otto poehl president of germanys bundesbank or 
central bank disagrees the uk is already in a recession he 
said last week 
kern of national westminister bank said the recession signals 
include a rise of 20000 in the number of jobless in august up 
from 13000 in july and a dun amp bradstreet corp report of a 35 
percent increase in business failures in the first nine months of 
1990 to the highest number in a decade 
he predicts economic growth will fall 08 percent in the third 
quarter and 1 percent in the fourth 
the economists offered one consolation that the setback wont 
be as bad as last time around during the last recession which 
began in the first quarter of 1980 economic contraction lasted 
five straight quarters 
it bears absolutely no comparison with 19801981 which was 
more painful said kevin darlington an economist at the london 
