<TEXT>
the millions of americans who sock away money in 
mutual funds didnt escape the pain and suffering on wall street 
during the past three months 
in addition to taking a toll on the blue chips of the dow jones 
industrial average the quarter that ended sunday belted funds 
across the board the persian gulf and the weakening economy were 
to blame 
there were very few places to hide in the third quarter 
said michael lipper whose company lipper analytical securities 
corp released its quarterly performance report on nearly 1800 
mutual funds wednesday 
lipper groups the funds into 27 categories based on the type of 
investments they make such as growth stocks or corporate bonds 
twothirds of these groups performed as poorly as they did in past 
recessions 
and the worst may be yet to come 
if we look at our measures of prior down markets compared with 
the present there may be more to go lipper said in an 
interview 
mutual funds are a popular way for individuals to invest in the 
stock bond and money markets by pooling the money of many 
investors mutual funds can buy a wider variety of securities than 
could a single investor limiting the risk should any of the 
investments go bad 
lippers figures were for funds that invest in stocks and 
taxable bonds they did not include money market mutual funds a 
popular investment alternative to savings accounts or funds that 
invest in taxexempt government bonds 
among the funds in the ranking those that invest in stocks 
fared the worst during the third quarter declining an average of 
155 percent that compares with a gain of 59 percent in the 
second quarter 
by comparison the 30stock dow jones average had a negative 
return of about 14 percent during the quarter assuming dividends 
were reinvested while standard amp poors 500 stock index another 
popular gauge of the stock market lost 137 percent lipper said 
a decline in stock funds also was not surprising given the 
unusually strong performance of these funds in the 1980s lipper 
said the topranked fund in the 10 years ended sept 30 fidelity 
investments magellan fund grew 6227 percent which he called 
unsustainably high 
the iraqi standoff also took a toll on many bond funds during 
the quarter since bond prices are extremely sensitive to the 
inflation caused by higher oil prices funds that invest in 
longterm taxable bonds declined 08 percent on average during the 
quarter compared with a gain of 32 percent in the second quarter 
the only groups of funds that grew were socalled world income 
funds which invest primarily in corporate bonds worldwide and 
gold funds which buy stock of gold mining companies as well as 
gold bullion and coins both were up about about 4 percent 
however individual funds in other groupings also rose 
including funds that invest in energy companies that benefitted 
from the oil price runup lipper said 
among the losers were funds that invest in science and 
technology companies financial services environmental companies 
and small businesses he said 
so what should an investor do 
david mclaughlin a financial adviser with chase investment 
counsel in charlottseville va said that depends on the objective 
of the investment 
if its for retirement it may be safe to stay in stock funds 
since the longterm trend of the stock market is up despite 
periodic slumps these investors should look for funds that have a 
good record in bear markets he said 
but for shorterterm investments consider short and 
mediumterm government securities mclaughlin said 
signs of a looming economic downturn were evident at the end of 
the second quarter lipper said when half of the lipper fund 
groups were performing as they did in previous recessions now 
with twothirds of them performing this way there is no doubt 
about the state of the economy he said 
but theres some shortterm positive news for fund investors he 
said 
were down far enough that we can have a rally in this fourth 
quarter as some investors sense the fund prices are cheap enough 
to make them attractive he said 
during the third quarter the topperforming fund was dreyfus 
capital value fund up nearly 13 percent in total return for the 
year ended sept 30 the top gainer was equity strategies a small 
fund that invests in bankrupt companies and is closed to new 
investors 
the worst performer for the quarter and the year ended sept 30 
was the prudent speculator leveraged fund which plummeted almost 
47 percent for the quarter and 51 percent for the year the fund 
borrows money to make its investors money go further increasing 
its risk in a down market lipper said 
for the past 10 years the worstperforming fund was the 44 wall 
street fund which dropped almost 83 percent in return lipper 
called it a stockpicking fund that has had a checkered 
career 
