<TEXT>
the four transactions prosecutors have chosen to 
prove that michael milken made a career of lawbreaking have one 
thing in common they all involve taking advantage of clients 
legal experts said that theme contrasts starkly with the defense 
portrait of the junk bond financier now and in the past as a man 
who made a few mistakes trying to better serve his customers 
in picking its silver bullets for a minitrial on allegations 
milken has not been formally charged with or pleaded guilty to he 
government wants to challenge a posture that milkens crimes were 
aberrant 
us district judge kimba wood ordered the unusual proceeding so 
she could better understand milken and devise an appropriate 
sentence 
three of the transactions involve some form of trading on 
nonpublic information available to milken about a client behavior 
now viewed as a sinister and deliberate breach and not a technical 
regulatory violation 
three of the allegations involve dealings with ivan f boesky 
the disgraced stock speculator who spent time in prison and gave 
the government the lions share of its dirt on milken 
contrary to his efforts to characterize the crimes he 
committed as petty milkens crimes were neither technical or 
victimless the government said in its lengthy presentencing 
memorandum 
the justice department claims against milken will be aired at 
the special hearing scheduled to begin oct 11 after wood on 
wednesday pushed back the start date by two days they were 
included in the governments memorandum designed to persuade wood 
to sentence milken to a long prison term 
milken former head of drexel burnham lambert incs highyield 
bond department faces a maximum 28 years in prison on six felonies 
to which he pleaded guilty in april after a nearly fouryear 
investigation 
the transactions to be taken up at the court hearing involve 
allegations of insider trading and other violations in trading 
securities of caesars world inc mgmua entertainment inc and 
storer communications inc and manipulation of wickes cos stock 
in court papers milkens attorneys said their client did 
nothing wrong in the transactions prosecutors plan to call up to 
14 witnesses to bolster their claims including boesky and several 
former drexel employees 
after milkens guilty plea his chief lawyer arthur liman 
noted that the six counts didnt involve insider trading and most 
of them were instances in which michael went too far in helping 
clients 
now the government is using legal precedent to offer the 
unproven claims at sentencing as evidence of years of wrongdoing 
judge wood asked prosecutors to limit their presentation to under 
five of about 35 unproven crimes 
the common denominator to the cases is the government is 
able to allege a breach of milkens and drexels duty to their 
client john c coffee jr a columbia university law professor 
who has followed the case closely said wednesday 
they tend to line up not as overzealousness on behalf of the 
client but predatory behavior against a client he said 
for instance the government claims milken illegally used 
information from his role advising turner broadcasting system about 
its 1985 acquisition of mgmua in a stock trading scheme with 
boesky that netted more than 3 million 
by buying large amounts of mgmua stock when the deal looked 
good the government alleges milken made handsome profits and 
generated a false sense of the deals viability when the deal 
appeared to sour milken and boesky stopped buying according to 
the governments presentencing memo milkens attorneys say the 
charges arent supported by the timing and prices of boeskys stock 
purchases 
in the storer transaction the government claims milken and 
boesky took advantage of a 1985 bidding war over the drexel client 
to buy and sell the companys stock making more than 1 million in 
profits milkens lawyers say the governments facts are wrong and 
milken did nothing illegal 
court papers also allege milken bribed money managers into 
buying risky storer securities by selling other storer securities 
at below market value the government alleges thatcash proceeds 
from the storer transactions surpassed 325 million with milken 
and another unidentified individual personally making 172 million 
in 1988 
the caesars transaction alleges milken in 1983 bought more than 
3 million in securities of the company after meeting with caesars 
executives to discuss restructuring its debt drexel managed the 
restructuring 
the defense memo said the government had offered a distorted 
picture of events in all the transactions and in some instances 
omitted evidence it has that would undermine the claims against 
milken 
