<TEXT>
despite expecting weak sales for the rest of 
this year and into next executives running federated department 
stores inc and allied stores corp are planning for the retailers 
to emerge from bankruptcy in 1991 
the sister retailers owned by financially distressed campeau 
corp on wednesday unveiled a business plan for the years through 
1996 that includes store closings but no outright sales of entire 
department store chains 
allen i questrom chairman and chief executive of allied and 
federated said the plan is the foundation on which to build a 
proposal to get out of bankruptcy proceedings 
he said allied and federated are making a push to get out of 
bankruptcy as quickly as possible because the longer the process 
drags on the costlier it will become 
neither questrom nor james m zimmerman president and chief 
operating officer of allied and federated would provide specific 
information on what the reorganization proposal would contain 
they refused to state how much money would be offered to 
creditors who collectively are owed around 77 billion most of 
the debt was amassed when canadas campeau bought allied and 
federated with borrowed money in the 1980s 
the judge supervising the bankruptcy in a cincinnati court last 
month gave federated stores inc the holding company for allied 
and federated until feb 28 to submit its reorganization plan 
companies operating under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy 
act are allotted time in which they have the exclusive right to 
come up with their own plans federated has been granted two 
extensions 
the executives said the reorganization plan which must be 
approved by creditors and us bankruptcy judge j vincent aug jr 
would not propose chopping off any allied or federated divisions 
among the nine chains they run are such wellknown retailers as 
bloomingdales bon marche burdines jordan marsh lazurus and 
richs 
the business plan presented wednesday projects operating 
earnings of allied and federated will more than double over the 
next six years 
operating profits which represent earnings before interest 
taxes depreciation and amortization are forecast to grow to 113 
billion in 1996 from an estimated 486 million this year 
the plan forecasts sales will rise to 989 billion in 1996 from 
722 billion in 1990 
questrom said the plan contains seven key elements that will be 
implemented throughout all allied and federated chains 
its not a plan that gets us to the moon its one thats 
realistic he said 
it focuses on basic merchandising matters and realigns various 
retail functions such as buying to make them more centralized an 
emphasis will be placed on keeping inventory fresh and improving 
the retailers abilities to respond quickly to changing consumer 
tastes 
it also envisions capital expenditures of 1 billion for 
remodeling and maintenance some 16 new stores plus some 
replacements are slated to be opened 
an unspecified number of store closings are contemplated 
zimmerman said stores that are failing to generate sufficient cash 
flow will be shut down but he declined to say which of allieds 
and federateds 250 stores are likely to go out of operation 
zimmerman and questrom said they believed pruning poor 
performers would provide a better return to creditors than trying 
to sell off whole divisions 
questrom who was recruited after allied and federated filed the 
bankruptcy petition jan 15 claimed progress will be slow in 
turning around the retailers in the near future the business plan 
assumes that the country will be in a virtual recession from about 
now through three quarters of next year 
he said allied and federated wont engage in drastic discounting 
this year to boost sales as they have ben accused of doing in the 
last christmas season 
he said the retailers havent bought too much merchandise so 
they wont be stuck with excessive inventories if business is as 
bad as some forecasters say it will be inventories at the end of 
august were about 330 million below the level of a year ago he 
said 
