<TEXT>
goldman sachs amp co said wednesday it has 
formed a large fund to invest in debtladen companies becoming one 
of the first prominent wall street brokerages to see opportunity in 
the excesses of the 1980s 
the venerable firm said that since april it has raised 683 
million for the fund from major us and foreign pension funds 
international banks university endowments insurance companies and 
individuals 
in addition the firm contributed 100 million of its own 
capital and will serve as general partner of the fund called the 
water street corp recovery fund i lp 
the funds strategy of targeting troubled firms marks a big 
departure from the goals of multimillion dollar funds of the 1980s 
which sought takeover targets or took companies private in highly 
leveraged deals 
other smaller investment concerns have seen potential rewards in 
getting distressed companies back on their feet but goldmans 
entry into the business signaled an interest on a much larger 
scale 
mikael salovaara head of goldmans leveraged finance group and 
supervisor of the funds daily activities anticipates annual 
returns of between 25 percent and 35 percent for investors who 
contributed a minimum 5 million to participate 
in taking large positions in financially troubled companies the 
fund will work as an active partner with managements whenever 
possible to help them restructure financially goldman said in a 
statement 
in the past four months salovaara said the fund has invested a 
total of 250 million in 10 companies most of which are fortune 
1000 concerns salovaara refused to identify them 
the restructuring we anticipate taking place will see a 
company shrink the amount of outstanding debt through 
bankruptcy if it comes to that and allow it to have a strengthened 
balance sheet salovaara said 
in the aggressive takeover days of the 1980s investment firms 
and partnerships raised millions to establish funds that invested 
in acquisitions and leveraged buyouts 
since then however the stock and junkbond markets have been 
battered and the economy has weakened forcing companies burdened 
with heavy debt loads into bankruptcy or restructurings 
coniston partners one of the most prominent takeover alliances 
of the 1980s said in june that it would disband a 700 million 
investment pool because of the continued shrinkage of the mergers 
and acquisitions market both suitable takeover targets and 
adequate financing had become scarce 
in its heyday conistons biggest targets included gillette co 
allegis corp and tw services inc coniston also agreed to 
participate in the employeeled buyout of united airlines 
salovaara said buying into trouble companies is clearly an 
area people need to look at we have a lot of companies with way 
too much debt on their balance sheets and unless that situation is 
changed outside of bankruptcy court it will end up being changed 
inside bankrutpcy court 
