a government report that finds no fault with 
last years temporary ban on fruit from chile is riddled with 
holes and replete with inaccuracies sen jesse helms rnc 
contends 
the report by the general accounting office the investigative 
arm of congress looked into the finding last year of two grapes 
from chile tainted with cyanide and the subsequent fiveday 
suspension of all fruit imports from chile 
a draft copy of the gao study circulated among news media on 
wednesday and helms says it should not be released in final form 
until the agency resolves several serious contradictions and 
unsupported assertions 
it is riddled with holes and replete with inaccuracies it 
simply does not measure up to the usual standards of the gao 
helms said in a letter to comptroller general charles a bowsher 
who heads the office 
gao has failed to present any analysis which would explain how 
fda was able to find only two contaminated grapes among millions 
before it then issued a false alarm banning chilean fruit and 
forcing its destruction in retail and wholesale outlets helms 
said this failure to provide any explanation for the miracle 
find alone invalidates the entire report 
the gao concluded after extensively evaluating fdas 
laboratory testing procedures that there was no merit to charges 
from chile that the tests were botched and fruit samples 
mishandled chilean growers say they lost 333 million by the 
fiveday import suspension 
we found that fdas discovery of cyanide in chilean grapes was 
