<DOCNO> AP901004-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the european community said thursday it 
would be willing to trim costly export subsidies for farmers 
although it still refused to embrace the sharp cuts demanded by the 
united states 
the communitys executive body unveiled its latest agriculture 
position in international trade talks that have been stalled by a 
bitter dispute between the 12nation trading bloc and the united 
states over farm payments 
ray macsharry the communitys top agriculture official said in 
a statement that the proposal strikes a careful balance between 
the needs of european farmers and the desire for a successful 
conclusion to the uruguay round of trade talks 
the fouryear negotiations which are scheduled to end in 
december are aimed at overhauling the world trading system they 
are designed to reduce barriers to trade in 15 areas including 
agriculture textiles and other manufactured goods and services 
such as banking and investment 
community officials have been fighting to protect their export 
subsidies which are designed to help local products find buyers on 
the world market they contend getting rid of the program would 
mean higher farm prices in europe and cost millions of jobs 
but the united states objects to the program as giving an unfair 
advantage to farmers overseas 
the communitys new proposal would cut farm payments by 30 
percent for such products as cereals rice sugar and livestock to 
1996 a 10 percent reduction is proposed for fruits vegetables and 
tobacco 
in return it wants to raise protective measures for such 
commodities as oilseeds 
the community also said it will not give new export subsidies 
for commodities not covered now 
moreover it said it is willing to translate these changes into 
numbers and then reevaluate this quantification 
the us mission to the european community had no immediate 
reaction to the proposal 
the ec statement appeared to signal the communitys willingness 
to bargain for reductions in export subsidies although not to the 
level the united states has been pushing for 
us trade representative carla hills has said the united states 
intends to propose a 10year plan for reductions of up to 70 
percent in domestic farm supports and import duties and even 
greater reductions in export subsidies 
the united states backed off a previous demand that export 
subsidies be eliminated but it still wants the community to widen 
its markets to foreign farm goods and slash farm payments that 
encourage overproduction 
the final offer must be approved next week by the member 
nations farm and trade ministers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

