a japanese company is trying to make a futuristic 
dream come true by opening an international video telephone service 
for the public 
six japanese women and a child sitting in the fffice of videocom 
international corp squealed with delight this week as they 
listened to and watched friends and relatives in singapore 
their friends spoke from a telephone office equipped with a 
similar terminal which looks like a small television with a 
builtin camera 
service between tokyo and los angeles is expected to start this 
week with new york and london to follow 
it was fun great said izumi sueda 36 who with a friend 
talked in tokyo with two friends in singapore 
but would they buy one most consumers around the world be 
skeptical analysts say 
there certainly will be individuals who are eager to see their 
relatives but i dont really think it will catch on said david 
benda head of research and a specialist in electronics for 
barclays de zoete wedd securities in japan 
american telephone amp telegraph co developed a videophone in the 
1950s but the company let it drop by the wayside in terms of 
marketing and product development said john murray senior 
technical support manager at atampts tokyo office 
atampt studies showed business people missed the personal contact 
of meetings people would still rather jump on the plane and rack 
up those frequentflier miles theres something about getting out 
of the office he said 
nippon telegraph amp telephone corp japans largest 
telecommunications company lists only 25 videophone customers 
among its 50 million customers about 200 customers use telephones 
that provide a series of still color pictures of speakers and 
listeners while 150000 use similar machines that provide black 
and white pictures ntt says 
analysts list a few reasons why videocoms service may also be 
limited in the immediate future 
one is cost a videophone costs more than 2200 compared to 
73 to 365 for an ordinary telephone ntt says 
meanwhile a 15minute call from japan to the united states 
costs 40 and from japan to singapore 49 
videocom which is 36 percentowned by kokusai denshin denwa 
co japans main international telecommunications company offers 
an international video conference service at roughly 10 times the 
price of a videophone call but with much clearer video pictures 
another problem is inconvenience at least two machines are 
needed for a video call moreover they need to be the same type 
because machines produced by different companies often cannot 
communicate said toshio satoh videocoms president 
for that reason videocoms service in singapore is limited to a 
single singapore telecom office and in los angeles to the office of 
a private company equal access corp 
the service operates only between 8 am and 8 pm local time 
in japan 
despite the drawbacks videocom hopes that several changes will 
help win customers 
one is the growing use of digital telecommunications lines 
which send information using digital instead of analog signals 
digital signals used by videocom are clearer than analog and can 
carry more information 
such digital technology will force us to take a second look 
at videophones atampts murray said 
fiber optic cables which will become increasingly common in the 
future can transmit even more information resulting in clearer 
pictures at lower cost images on videocoms equipment 
manufactured by mitsubishi corp using kdd technology now are 
fuzzy and slightly jerky 
also the international telegraph and telephone consultative 
committee is expected this year to set standards for videophones 
that should encourage manufacturers in the united states europe 
and japan to make machines that can communicate with each other he 
said 
if people are accustomed to the video telephone then in the 
near future there will be an opportunity to promote or market our 
equipment to them satoh said 
more demand will bring lower prices within one or two years 
he said 
