<TEXT>
new england telephone and new york telephone 
have agreed to pay 14 million to the us treasury and a 355 
million rebate to longdistance customers to resolve allegations 
they overcharged customers through a subsidiary the federal 
communications commission said thursday 
the fcc in february said it intended to fine the two companies 
14 million a record amount over apparent violations of fcc 
rules governing transactions between regulated telephone companies 
and unregulated affiliates 
the fcc had ordered the companies to return 355 million to 
customers because of alleged overcharges to nyt and net by materiel 
enterprises co an unregulated nynex purchasing subsidiary 
the 14 million payment announced thursday is a voluntary 
contribution and not a fine the fcc said under whats known as a 
consent decree nynex admitted no guilt and the fcc said it had 
made no findings of wrongdoing and was ending its enforcement 
action 
nynex agreed to the 355 million rebate to be made within 30 
days and would take other accounting steps to resolve allegations 
of excess profits on plant and equipment purchased from the 
materiel enterprises subsidiary 
local phone rates will not be affected 
we hope this puts to rest any questions concerning nynexs 
desire to comply with all fcc regulations and policies in 
transactions among affiliate companies nynex chairman william c 
ferguson said in a statement 
the agreement ends one of several pending federal or state 
actions against nynex one of the seven regional bell holding 
companies created in 1984 from the old bell system 
nynex also has been the focus of investigations that new york 
telephone suppliers helped pay for bawdy parties and prostitutes at 
annual conventions of company employees in florida from 1984 to 
1988 nynex has denied that any ratepayer funds were involved in 
the conventions 
in may the justice department filed a onecount criminal 
indictment alleging nynex violated the information services 
restrictions on the regional bell companies nynex denied 
wrongdoing 
on wednesday new york state utility regulators authorized a 
study into whether nynex should be forced to divest new york 
telephone 
the fcc in february had said materiel enterprises apparently 
overcharged nyt and net by 1185 million from 1984 to 1988 of 
that the fcc said 355 million was passed through to 
longdistance customers 
long distance companies such as atampt mci and us sprint pay 
access charges to nynex and other regional bells and those 
charges are figured into longdistance prices 
toby webb nynexs vice president for government affairs said 
thursday he could not estimate how much the 355 million rebate 
would affect longdistance prices for new york and new england 
phone customers 
webb said nynex had agreed to the latest consent decree in order 
to avoid a potentially long court battle over accounting and 
purchasing procedures that no longer were in effect materiel 
enterprises was merged into new york telephone and new england 
telephone earlier this year thus making materiel a fully regulated 
company under fcc rules 
the agreement is preferable to engaging in prolonged 
litigation over past events and practices which have been 
changed webb said it is time to focus fully on meeting the 
needs of our customers 
