<TEXT>
forget those dour economic forecasts for a couple 
days business leaders are trying to put a bright face on 
massachusetts by giving residents a small bargain for buying stock 
in the states companies 
the effort was dubbed take stock in massachusetts business 
it opened with the start of trading thursday on the boston stock 
exchange and the window will close at the end of fridays session 
for the two days the stock exchange agreed to waive transaction 
fees for brokerage firms that in turn waived commissions for 
residents who buy stock in companies headquartered in 
massachusetts 
its an opportunity for the people of massachusetts to be 
partners in their own economic future said gerald scott 
organizer of the program who launched the sesion by ringing an 
oldfashioned school bell 
lately the states economic future has looked grim 
unemployment has risen sharply as the oncepowerful computer 
financial and construction sectors have suffered heavy beatings 
but the organizers of the stock program insisted that all is not 
bad in massachusetts some companies are performing well 
larry vale a spokesman for keane inc a bostonbased software 
company pointed to his firm as an example vale who participated 
in thursdays opening said keanes net earnings grew by 24 percent 
last year 
in this gloom and doom mentality people tend to forget that 
below the surface there are good companies he said 
even some companies that have been battered recently can be good 
stock buys investment analysts said ed sullivan representing 
dean witter reynolds inc mentioned digital equipment corp and 
bank of boston corp as two highprofile companies that have been 
hurt recently but should perform well in the long run 
for investors who think they have found a good buy they will 
avoid paying commissions that range from about 1 percent to 3 
percent that means a person buying 5000 worth of stock will save 
anywhere from 50 to 150 
people taking advantage of the program must buy at least 1000 
worth of stock but no more than 25000 
organizers cautioned that investors shouldnt buy stock simply 
because they can save a small amount of money on commissions 
instead the main reason is to make a longterm investment 
similarly scott said he didnt expect a tidal wave of instate 
investments during the twoday program but he said it should make 
massachusetts residents more interested in and aware of the 
different companies based in the state 
