a powerful threeday surge in pork belly futures prices peaked 
thursday on the chicago mercantile exchange as buying interest 
sparked by a surprising government hogsandpigs report exhausted 
itself 
frozen pork bellies for delivery in february closed above 
wednesdays closing price but below the days high of 649 cents a 
pound which represented a gain of nearly 12 percent since friday 
on other commodity markets livestock futures were mixed energy 
futures were mixed precious metals retreated and grains and 
soybeans were mixed 
pork bellies settled 65 cent lower to 25 cent higher with 
february up 25 cent at 6445 cents a pound 
pork bellies had risen the permitted daily limit of 2 cents a 
pound monday tuesday and wednesday in reaction to fridays 
quarterly hogsandpigs inventory 
the agriculture department report included an estimate of the 
number of pigs born during the summer that was 2 percent lower than 
in 1989 most market analysts had expected summer farrowings to be 
unchanged or even a little higher than a year earlier 
the unexpectedly low number means the number of hogs available 
for slaughter in the first quarter of 1991 when those piglets 
mature also will be below the yearago level said charles levitt 
senior livestock analyst with shearson lehman brothers inc 
he said most observers had expected the slaughter rate to level 
off or begin to rise in the first quarter 
what we did not expect was that the decline in slaughters from 
a year earlier would be extended into next year which means its 
going to be at least next spring before we get increases in the hog 
slaughter compared to the year previous levitt said 
the market also was supported recently by indications that 
frozen belly supplies are virtually depleted he said 
phil stanley a livestock consultant for dec futures inc said 
the relative weakness thursday in the belly market also reflected 
profittaking by traders who had taken bullish positions ahead of 
the report 
in livestock trading on the merc live cattle futures settled 
08 cent to 33 cent lower with october at 7975 cents a pound 
