<TEXT>
the broadest measure of the nations money 
supply fell in the week ended sept 24 while the secondbroadest 
measure grew slightly the federal reserve board reported thursday 
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose to a seasonally 
adjusted 33162 billion from 33156 billion the previous week 
an even broader measure m3 fell to a seasonally adjusted 
40858 billion from 40933 billion 
the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 rose to a 
seasonally adjusted 8217 billion from 8206 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging its monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply 
measures 
the growth rate in m2 in the past 52 weeks was 5 percent which 
is within the feds target range of 3 percent to 7 percent the 
growth rate in the past year in m3 was 18 percent which is within 
the feds target range of 1 percent to 5 percent the fed has not 
set a target for m1 growth since early 1987 
for the latest 13 weeks m2 averaged 3299 billion a 3 percent 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks 
m3 averaged 40834 billion up 15 percent while m1 rose 42 
percent to an average of 8152 billion 
in other reports 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system at the discount window excluding extended credit 
averaged 503 million a day in the week ended wednesday down from 
513 million the previous week 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the 
monetary base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank 
reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and 
in circulation was 3184 billion in the twoweek period ended 
wednesday down from 3188 billion two weeks earlier 
</TEXT>
