<TEXT>
the czechoslovak government 
facing a winter of higher oil costs and dwindling soviet supplies 
imposed higher oil and gasoline prices thursday and appealed to 
moscow for help 
measures taken by a crisis team of government officials 
announced in a tv address by economics minister vladimir dlouhy 
are aimed at stemming a near panic about potential fuel shortages 
the state ctk news agency said 
to make it simple the main problem is that oil is much more 
expensive now dlouhy said on national television 
the soviet union for years the main oil supplier in east bloc 
countries is unable to fulfill its quotas at the same time it 
will begin demanding scarce convertible currency for its oil 
beginning jan 1 
many of the countries have lost supplies of iraqi oil because of 
their support for the un sanctions against saddam hussein and 
their fragile economies are facing much higher prices on the world 
market 
elsewhere poland announced it would import oil from iran to 
make up for dwindling soviet supplies and losses caused by the gulf 
crisis 
dlouhy estimated czechoslovakias loss because of the gulf 
crisis at about 14 billion 
beginning midnight friday czechoslovak consumers will be 
allowed to buy only about six gallons of gasoline in october at the 
official price of about 3 a gallon additional gasoline will cost 
about 25 percent more 
motor and heating oil will be increased from about 224 dollars 
to 3 a gallon 
new limits for november will be announced later ctk said 
premier marian calfa appealed for urgent talks with soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev and premier nikolai i ryzkov on 
faltering soviet oil supplies 
soviet supplies began falling in the first half of the year and 
the shortfall led to a panic in july that forced the government to 
drive up the price by 50 percent ctk said 
ctk quoted finance minister vaclav klaus as saying that he could 
not rule out more changes in wholesale prices by the end of the 
year 
