<TEXT>
ford motor co on thursday gave the united auto 
workers union a comprehensive proposal for a new national labor 
contract that according to one company official mirrors the 
contract reached with general motors corp 
the union which ratified a threeyear agreement with gm late 
last month has insisted that the uawgm agreement serve as a model 
for contracts with ford and chrysler corp 
except for one provision on overtime pay ford isnt expected to 
have trouble agreeing to a contract similar to gms 
i think probably ford has fallen in line with that said the 
company official speaking on condition of anonymity 
the uaw agreements with the big three cover more than 450000 
active workers about 300000 at gm about 100000 at ford and 
about 60000 at chrysler 
the gmuaw agreement raises base wages by 3 percent in the first 
year and includes lumpsum increases equal to 3 percent of base 
wages in the second and third years costofliving protection on 
wages would be maintained and retirees will receive more money 
it guarantees income for employees laid off for more than 36 
weeks during the life of the agreement and makes no changes in 
healthcare provisions 
the pattern agreement also contains a new provision boosting the 
penalty for excessive overtime worked in a week ford has been 
using overtime much more liberally than the two other us 
automakers and the union has suggested it be curtailed and the 
company hire more workers 
neither company nor union officials would talk about specific 
provisions of the proposal offered thursday they issued a joint 
statement saying only that the proposal was delivered and that the 
union was studying it 
a union official who also requested anonymity said studying 
the document and holding some meetings of bargaining subcommittees 
would take negotiators into thursday night 
on tuesday uaw president owen bieber said he expected 
negotiations with ford could be completed by the end of the week 
company vice president peter pestillo said that was possible 
after a contract is ratified by ford workers the union will 
turn to chrysler where it faces an uncertain reception the no 3 
automaker has said it may not be able to afford a contract similar 
to the other autoworkers but the union is expected to push for 
the model agreement 
