<DOCNO> AP901004-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
american computer and semiconductor 
makers feuding for years over a computer chip trade agreement with 
japan announced a new trade plan thursday that could bring lower 
prices to consumers 
the proposed pact which industry leaders said received an 
encouraging response from bush administration officials would end 
price controls on imported memory chips and remove an irritant in 
usjapanese relations 
the proposal for a new 5year agreement to succeed the 1986 
usjapan semiconductor trade agreement set to expire next july 
31 marks the first time chipmakers and computer makers have joined 
to achieve the same trade policy 
us chipmakers pushed for the 1986 agreement to stop japanese 
companies from dumping unfairly priced memory chips in the 
united states but us computer makers complained the agreement 
kept prices high for a key component of their products 
if the new pact is adopted it could bring down the cost of 
memory devices and be a bonanza for consumers and computer makers 
analysts said 
top executives of both industries represented by the 
semiconductor industry association a trade group and the computer 
systems policy project worked for months on the new proposal 
the computer group founded last year includes the chief 
executives of international business machines corp 
hewlettpackard co apple computer inc sun microsystems inc 
tandem computers inc compaq computer corp and five other 
companies 
wilfred corrigan chief executive officer of lsi logic corp and 
chairman of the semiconductor group said in washington that the 
proposal is based on the premise that open markets and the 
availability of semiconductors at reasonable prices will promote 
the health of the us electronics industry foster better 
relations between the us and japan and allow market forces to 
function freely 
rod canion chief executive officer of compaq and vice chairman 
of the computer group said it is important that both groups speak 
with a united voice on issues of hightech trade 
industry analysts praised the two sides for putting aside their 
differences 
the fact that they can speak with one voice to congress and 
the administration is very significant said marc elliot of 
dataquest inc in san jose i think youll see a lot more 
cooperation out of the bush administration because of that 
instead of using fair market values to determine the prices 
at which japanese chips are sold in the united states the proposal 
calls for fast track investigations by the commerce department 
of dumping allegations 
anything that takes away from the fair market value and that 
level of accountability is going to be favorably looked on by the 
japanese elliot said they consider themselves to be honorable 
people who dont need to be treated like children i think thats 
what this trade policy did i think it will ease some of the 
animosity that has existed 
the proposal acknowledges the success of the current trade 
agreement and lawsuits in getting japanese companies to stop 
dumping and urges less government involvement it calls for a halt 
in an investigation into dumping of memory chips called drams 
this proposal is very promising in that it focuses on the real 
issue which is access to the japanese market said michael 
murphy editor of the california technology stock letter 
the proposal seeks to boost the us share of overall 
semiconductor sales in japan to 20 percent by the end of 1992 and 
calls for review of further targets in 1993 
when the original trade agreement was signed the us had 
about 10 percent of the japanese semiconductor market and they 
had about 10 percent of our market murphy said now we have 
about 11 percent of their market and they have about 17 percent of 
ours so the original agreement actually caused the problem in my 
view 
one of the problems he said is that about 20 percent of us 
chip production is for military devices that the japanese dont 
need and about 40 percent of japans demand is for cheap chips for 
consumer products which us chip companies arent interested in 
making 
so by the time you exclude military and consumer chips you 
wind up with a relatively small area in which we make chips that 
they use he said 
the biggest beneficiaries in the semiconductor industry he 
said would be the us companies that make standard 
microprocessors such as texas instruments inc lsi logic and 
chips amp technologies inc 
</TEXT>
