<TEXT>
pipeline companies that allegedly 
profited illegally from higher natural gas prices in the early 
1980s agreed thursday to a 432 million settlement in an antitrust 
suit brought by utilities 
consumers should get 100 percent of the settlement after legal 
costs probably in the form of credits on their bills and lower 
rates according to the attorneys general of missouri and kansas 
the settlement also includes a guarantee of natural gas for the 
next 20 years at what is expected to be lower than market rates 
said attorneys general william webster of missouri and bob stephan 
of kansas in announcing the settlement 
agreeing to the settlement were amoco production co oxy usa 
inc and williams natural gas co 
amoco and oxy had settled a week ago but details of the 
agreement were not released because of a gag order issued by us 
district judge earl oconnor 
the case against williams then went to trial the parties 
negotiated until 4 am thursday cleaned up details later in the 
morning and oconnor dismissed the case late in the morning 
none of the defendants admitted liability in the settlement 
oxy said in a statement released late thursday its share of the 
settlement comes to 245 million amoco and williams would not 
disclose the amounts they agreed to pay 
irrespective of ones feelings regarding the merit of our 
position you reach a point where it makes more sense to put the 
issue behind you and turn your attention to the business at hand 
this is such a time said joseph h williams chairman and chief 
executive officer of tulsa oklabased williams 
details of the plan must be approved by the missouri public 
service commission and the kansas corporation commission 
the case was taken to court starting in 1984 by utilities and 
the states the suits which alleged antitrust violations from 1979 
to 1984 were then consolidated 
