a plan to repay more than 54 million 
in overdue bills to subcontractors who worked on donald trumps taj 
mahal casino resort was filed thursday with the federal securities 
and exchange commission 
the casino said it had already paid 15 million in cash and 
would pay another on 32 million in cash by oct 15 for 
construction work on the mammoth casino which cost 1 billion to 
build 
in addition the casino pledged 364 million in notes that will 
come due on aug 15 1995 the notes bear 8 percent interest in the 
fourth year and 10 percent in the fifth year according to the 
filing 
at least four subcontractors who did not go along with the deal 
have gone to court to enforce payment from the manhattan developer 
the taj mahal which opened amid much hoopla on april 2 has not 
taken in the 13 million a day that analysts have said it needs to 
break even parts of the property remain unfinished 
the state casino control commission must approve the plan to 
repay the subcontractors the commission has scheduled hearings 
oct 30 to examine the financial stability of the taj mahal and 
trumps other two casinos 
