<TEXT>
thirteen american airlines customers are 
seeking more than 45 million in two lawsuits alleging the company 
reneged on an agreement to honor its obligations under the 
frequentflyer program 
the lawsuits filed tuesday in champaign county circuit court 
both accuse american of breach of contract fraud and violating 
federal racketeering law 
tom stack a spokesman in chicago for dallasbased american 
said thursday the company had not seen the lawsuits and could not 
comment on them 
american has responded to the flyers complaints previously that 
they had violated the rules of the program called aadvantage 
by transferring and selling mileage credits 
one lawsuit comprising 49 counts on behalf of eight frequent 
flyers says american has failed to honor a settlement it reached 
with the flyers after they filed a series of consumer fraud 
complaints with the illinois attorney general in 1988 
in the settlement american said it would let the flyers and 
others use the credits they had earned under the frequent flyer 
program according to the lawsuit 
the lawsuit seeks 650000 in actual damages and 10 million in 
punitive damages punitive damages could be tripled under the 
federal racketeering influenced and corrupt organizations act also 
called rico said the plaintiffs attorney jeffrey frederick 
the second lawsuit comprising 32 counts on behalf of five 
plaintiffs alleges that american failed to honor tickts earned by 
frequent flyers who were not part of the settlement agreement 
frederick said thursday 
that lawsuit seeks 100000 in actual damages and 5 million in 
punitive damages 
theres got to be some changes in all these programs because 
no one really knows whats going on and the airlines are changing 
the rules at their own whim said frederick 
he said the lawsuits were filed in champaign for the convenience 
for many of the plaintiffs who live nearby and for himself 
american forced a newlywed couple to cancel their honeymoon 
plans by refusing to honor their frequent flyer credit on reserved 
flights to new york and on the concorde to london the second 
lawsuit alleged frederick said reservations had been confirmed the 
day before 
he said customers also typically were allowed to fly to a 
distant destination such as hawaii on frequent flyer credit 
only to have the airline refuse to honor their returntrip tickets 
the customers then were forced to pay full fare to get home 
frederick said 
like many other airlines american has been the target of 
previous lawsuits on behalf of angry frequent flyers who claimed 
the airlines were failing to live up to their promises 
one of the lawsuits a 2yearold class action on behalf of 9 
million american airlines customers is pending in illinois 
appellate court said gilbert gordon an attorney for the 
plaintiffs in chicago 
</TEXT>
